{"type":"message_start","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"For each crate under rust_pkg and each crate under crack_demo, we want you to run a sub-agent that will:\n- check if the crate Cargo.toml has [lints]workspace=true and only if it does not, add it\n- cd into the crate and run \"cargo build\" and save the answer to a /tmp file\n- write docstrings to satisfy every single docs-related warning in that file\n- review using \"git diff\" from inside the crate every file to double check no code was corrupted\n- run \"cargo build\" from inside the crate every file or two to verify nothing was wreckd\n- when everything is done, do a final run by running \"./test.sh\" from inside the crate , if it exists (the one in the crate, NOT the one in the workspace root)\neach subagent will only edit code for its own personal crate it was assigned to. Each subagent will only ever add docstring comments after researching how the code connects to its space around, and why that code is the way it is. Keep it short, at most one paragraph of 3 lines of 80 characters width.\n\nYou, as the coordinator, should not read any rust code yourself. You should, however, use \"find\" to get all the Cargo toml inside the folders we care about, and then write out its tasks into the spawn_coder tool with planning off. After all your sub-agents return for all the crates, run a final ./test.sh from the workspace root, and a final \"cargo check --all\" to verify we have not missed any documentation. In your prompts that you write to the sub-agents, make sure to mention the gotchas and pitfalls in _slop/rust-docs-gotchas.md"}],"timestamp":1784666435913}}
{"type":"message_end","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"For each crate under rust_pkg and each crate under crack_demo, we want you to run a sub-agent that will:\n- check if the crate Cargo.toml has [lints]workspace=true and only if it does not, add it\n- cd into the crate and run \"cargo build\" and save the answer to a /tmp file\n- write docstrings to satisfy every single docs-related warning in that file\n- review using \"git diff\" from inside the crate every file to double check no code was corrupted\n- run \"cargo build\" from inside the crate every file or two to verify nothing was wreckd\n- when everything is done, do a final run by running \"./test.sh\" from inside the crate , if it exists (the one in the crate, NOT the one in the workspace root)\neach subagent will only edit code for its own personal crate it was assigned to. Each subagent will only ever add docstring comments after researching how the code connects to its space around, and why that code is the way it is. Keep it short, at most one paragraph of 3 lines of 80 characters width.\n\nYou, as the coordinator, should not read any rust code yourself. You should, however, use \"find\" to get all the Cargo toml inside the folders we care about, and then write out its tasks into the spawn_coder tool with planning off. After all your sub-agents return for all the crates, run a final ./test.sh from the workspace root, and a final \"cargo check --all\" to verify we have not missed any documentation. In your prompts that you write to the sub-agents, make sure to mention the gotchas and pitfalls in _slop/rust-docs-gotchas.md"}],"timestamp":1784666435913}}
